{"key":"processedPost-9430858","value":{"id":9430858,"first":9429286,"last":9439075,"when":1229292917,"utime":"12/15/08 12:15 AM","content":"The truth is, you probably don't 'need' to fan at all with a shotgun, but as soon as I say that, someone will get a case of cobweb mold from still air.&nbsp;  If there's good circulation in your house and you're growing a CO2 tolerant species such as cubensis, you really don't <i>have</i> to fan.&nbsp; However, air exchange is the number 1 pinning trigger, so it never hurts to have as much as possible.&nbsp; Mist as required to make up for any lost moisture from fresh air exchange.&nbsp; Nobody can say how often to mist, because too many variables are at play.&nbsp; You have to use your eyeballs and a good hygrometer to know how often.<br /><br />Mist the cakes and perlite.&nbsp; The old advice to mist the walls only makes about as much sense as washing your car by spraying the hose on the ground around it.<br />RR","title":"Re: caps folding up? and some FC questions... (pics)","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}